-- P0-19 (constrained-receiver arm), PRELUDE half: merely DEFINING a top-level function
-- whose name collides with a prelude interface method (`eq`) must not break the
-- prelude's own constrained bodies.
--
-- On the flat check path the program is core ++ user, so core's constrained standalone
-- `neq : Eq a => a -> a -> Bool` (`neq x y = not (eq x y)`) had its `eq` occurrence
-- routed through the definer-shadow path: an UNGROUNDED receiver (`x : a`) was treated
-- as the STANDALONE (P0-19 S5) and `enforceStandaloneDomain` unified `a := Int` against
-- THIS file's `eq : Int -> Int -> Int` — so `not (eq x y)` became `not Int` and the whole
-- program was rejected with `Type mismatch: Bool vs Int` pointed at line 1.  Defining a
-- top-level `eq` (or `compare`) was simply impossible.  `a` is dict-bound by `Eq a =>`,
-- so that occurrence DISPATCHES; it is not the standalone.
--
-- `neq 1 2` here proves the prelude's constrained body still dispatches correctly (True).
eq : Int -> Int -> Int
eq a b = a + b + 100

main = println (neq 1 2)
